ts. I will proceed to visit the most relevant links from the batch/command-line options search to gather detailed information.\\n\\n<code>\\nurls = [\\n    \"https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/commandline_tool.html\",\\n    \"https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/workflows/batch_processing/batch-processing.html\",\\n    \"https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine3/issues/1432\",\\n    \"https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine/issues/1827\"\\n]\\nfor url in urls:\\n    page_content = go_to_url_tool(url)\\n    print(f\"Content from {url}:\", page_content)\\n    print(\"\\\\n\" + \"=\"*80 + \"\\\\n\")  # Print separator between pages\\n</code>'}], tool_calls=None, raw=None, token_usage=None), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.TOOL_CALL: 'tool-call'>, content=[{'type': 'text', 'text': 'Calling tools:\\n[{\\'id\\': \\'call_2\\', \\'type\\': \\'function\\', \\'function\\': {\\'name\\': \\'python_interpreter\\', \\'arguments\\': \\'urls = [\\\\n    \"https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/commandline_tool.html\",\\\\n    \"https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/workflows/batch_processing/batch-processing.html\",\\\\n    \"https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine3/issues/1432\",\\\\n    \"https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine/issues/1827\"\\\\n]\\\\nfor url in urls:\\\\n    page_content = go_to_url_tool(url)\\\\n    print(f\"Content from {url}:\", page_content)\\\\n    print(\"\\\\\\\\n\" + \"=\"*80 + \"\\\\\\\\n\")  # Print separator between pages\\'}}]'}], tool_calls=None, raw=None, token_usage=None), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.TOOL_RESPONSE: 'tool-response'>, content=[{'type': 'text', 'text': 'Observation:\\nExecution logs:\\nContent from https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/commandline_tool.html: \\n```json\\n{\\n  \"action\": \"go_to_url_tool(url=\\'https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/commandline_tool.html\\')\",\\n  \"observation\": \"Tile: Command line tool (batch mode) - mzmine documentation\\\\n            [Start of page]\\\\n\\\\nCommand line tool (batch mode)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 13\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 29\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 13\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 29\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Command line tool (batch mode)\\\\n\\\\nCommand line tool (batch mode)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 LC-IMS-MS feature detection\\\\n\\\\nLC-IMS-MS feature detection\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 MS2 scan pairing\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 MALDI MS2 scan pairing (SIMSEF)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 13C isotope filter (isotope grouper)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 m/z mobility region extraction\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Same RT and m/z range gap filler\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Precursor search in local spectral MS/MS library\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 MS2 similarity search\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Interactive Ion Identity Molecular Networks\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 4D features plot (Kendrick)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 ECN (Equivalent Carbon Number) models\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Untargeted LC-IMS-MS workflow\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 LC-MS and LC-IMS-MS data comparison\\\\n\\\\n# Command-line interface (CLI) for headless batch mode\\\\u00b6\\\\n\\\\nCommand-line arguments offer a variety of options that generally override the corresponding parameters in the preferences.\\\\n\\\\nThe CLI option for mzmine offers to run one batch file (-batch). This batch file can be easily generated by another script\\\\n\\\\nor can be a standardized batch file for an analytical method that is applied to multiple datasets.\\\\n\\\\nThe most convenient way to apply a batch file to other datasets is to specify the **-input** and **-output**\\\\n\\\\narguments to process all import files and to redirect all outputs to another directory. See examples below\\\\n\\\\nfor how to process all .mzML files in a folder and to redirect outputs to a new directory and base filename.\\\\n\\\\nRunning mzmine in CLI mode requires a user. Either login via graphical-user interface (GUI) or via command-line argument **-login** (web browser support required) or via **-login-console**.\\\\n\\\\nThen locate the user file in your system USER directory under /.mzmine/users/. The most recently active user is automatically selected for mzmine processing,\\\\n\\\\nbut an .mzuser file can be passed in as command-line argument to **-user**.\\\\n\\\\nFor command-line mode, the mzmine\\\\\\\\_console.exe is preferred as it will print the logging output to the console.\\\\n\\\\nAn easy way to start mzmine with arguments is to create a shortcut to the mzmine.exe or the mzmine\\\\\\\\_console.exe, right-click, and define the target with additional arguments. This example runs mzmine in batch mode (headless), imports the specified batch file, overrides the memory management to **none** (which is the default), effectively using memory mapping to store and access spectral, centroid, and feature data from temporary files stored in the defined temp directory. By leaving out the *memory* or *temp* arguments, the values stored in the current *preferences* file will be used, or the default values if no *preferences* file was found.\\\\n\\\\n**Login to a user in command-line mode**\\\\n\\\\n\\\\\"C:\\\\\\\\Program Files\\\\\\\\mzmine\\\\\\\\mzmine_console.exe\\\\\" -login\\\\n\\\\n\\\\\"C:\\\\\\\\Program Files\\\\\\\\mzmine\\\\\\\\mzmine_console.exe\\\\\" -login-console\\\\n\\\\n**Process all .mzML files in a folder by the provided batch file, redirect output files to results folder and use a base filename, various export modules add a specific suffix**\\\\n\\\\n\\\\\"C:\\\\\\\\Program Files\\\\\\\\mzmine\\\\\\\\mzmine_console.exe\\\\\" -user \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\user\\\\\\\\testuser.mzuser\\\\\" -batch \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\batch\\\\\\\\my_batch_file.mzbatch\\\\\" -input \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\Data\\\\\\\\*.mzML\\\\\" -output \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\Results\\\\\\\\basename\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n**Defining the temp folder, otherwise uses the one specified in local configuration**\\\\n\\\\n\\\\\"C:\\\\\\\\Program Files\\\\\\\\mzmine\\\\\\\\mzmine_console.exe\\\\\" -user \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\user\\\\\\\\testuser.mzuser\\\\\" -batch \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\batch\\\\\\\\my_batch_file.mzbatch\\\\\" -temp \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\tmpmzmine\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n**Start mzmine batch with memory mapping (DEFAULT)**\\\\n\\\\n\\\\\"C:\\\\\\\\Program Files\\\\\\\\mzmine\\\\\\\\mzmine_console.exe\\\\\" -user \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\user\\\\\\\\testuser.mzuser\\\\\" -batch \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\batch\\\\\\\\my_batch_file.mzbatch\\\\\" -memory none -temp \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\tmpmzmine\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n**Start mzmine batch on machines with enough memory (RAM) with -memory all** this will disable memory mapping to temporary files.\\\\n\\\\n\\\\\"C:\\\\\\\\Program Files\\\\\\\\mzmine\\\\\\\\mzmine_console.exe\\\\\" -user \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\user\\\\\\\\testuser.mzuser\\\\\" -batch \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\batch\\\\\\\\my_batch_file.mzbatch\\\\\" -memory all -temp \\\\\"D:\\\\\\\\tmpmzmine\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\nIf the app was installed to the *Applications* folder, run this command in the terminal to run a batch file:\\\\n\\\\n/Applications/mzmine.app/Contents/MacOS/mzmine -user \\\\\"path/to/testuser.mzuser\\\\\" -batch /path/to/batch_file.mzbatch\\\\n\\\\n/Applications/mzmine.a\",\\n  \"reward\": 1.0\\n}\\n```\\n\\n\\n================================================================================\\n\\nContent from https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/workflows/batch_processing/batch-processing.html: \\n```json\\n{\\n  \"action\": \"go_to_url_tool(url=\\'https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/workflows/batch_processing/batch-processing.html\\')\",\\n  \"observation\": \"Tile: Batch processing - mzmine documentation\\\\n            [Start of page]\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 13\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 29\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 13\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 29\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Command line tool (batch mode)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 LC-IMS-MS feature detection\\\\n\\\\nLC-IMS-MS feature detection\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 MS2 scan pairing\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 MALDI MS2 scan pairing (SIMSEF)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 13C isotope filter (isotope grouper)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 m/z mobility region extraction\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Same RT and m/z range gap filler\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Precursor search in local spectral MS/MS library\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 MS2 similarity search\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Interactive Ion Identity Molecular Networks\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 4D features plot (Kendrick)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 ECN (Equivalent Carbon Number) models\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 Untargeted LC-IMS-MS workflow\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 How to run batch processing\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 LC-MS and LC-IMS-MS data comparison\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 How to run batch processing\\\\n\\\\nBesides the interactive GUI, MZmine allows the user to run processing workflows in an automated manner using the \\\\\"batch mode\\\\\". Entire processing pipelines (including data import/export) can be run with few clicks, or even through the command-line application. This makes MZmine suitable to be integrated into automated data analysis pipelines (e.g. QC systems).\\\\n\\\\nBatch files (XML format) are essentially lists of tasks run by MZmine one after another. Any of the methods available in MZmine 3 can be included in the batch file.\\\\n\\\\n## **How to run batch processing**\\\\u00b6\\\\n\\\\nWhen a new step is added to the queue its parameter setup dialog is shown. The \\\\\"Set paramaters\\\\\" button allows the user to modify a step\\'s parameter settings. The \\\\\"Clear\\\\\" button removes all steps. The \\\\\"Load\\\\\" and \\\\\"Save\\\\\" buttons make it possible to read and write batch steps to XML files.\\\\n\\\\nThe first step of a batch queue is performed on those raw data files and/or peak lists selected by the user. The remaining steps are performed on the results produced by each preceding step (File/Feature list selection must be set to *Those created by previous batch step*). For example, if the first step of the batch queue is the ADAP chromatogram builder, it will produce peak lists as a result. If the following step were Peak list deconvolution then it will be performed on the peak lists produced by the preceding Chromatogram builder step.\\\\n\\\\n**Tip** MZmine \\\\\"remembers\\\\\" the last settings used.\\\\n\\\\nThe processing wizard is inteded to quickly set up a general workflow for the processing of untargeted LC-MS and LC-IM-MS data. By clicking the \\\\\"Set default\\\\\" button, default settings for mass and feature detection are also provided according to the selected MS type (Orbitrap or TOF) and LC system (UHPLC or HPLC). Once the desired parameters have been set, hit the \\\\\"Build batch\\\\\" botton and a pre-populated batch window will open up.\\\\n\\\\nMS type: When TOF is selected, the \\\\\"Ion mobility\\\\\" can be enabled\\\\n\\\\nMS1 and MS2 noise level:\\\\n\\\\nScan to scan m/z tolerance:\\\\n\\\\nFeature to feature m/z tolerance:\\\\n\\\\nMin samples per aligned feature:\\\\n\\\\nOnly keep feature with 13C:\\\\n\\\\nThe default settings were optimized on sample datasets used during the MZmine 3 development. Although probably suitable for many appications, it is strongly recommended not to blindly rely on them. Rather, optimal processing parameters should be chosen based on the LC-(IM)-MS system performance and data acquisition settings.\\\\n\\\\nNovember 24, 2022 21:13:07\\\\n\\\\nThis documentation is licensed under the MIT License (MIT).\\\\n\\\\n[End of page]\\\\n        \",\\n  \"reward\": 1.0\\n}\\n```\\n\\n\\n================================================================================\\n\\nContent from https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine3/issues/1432: \\n```json\\n{\\n  \"action\": \"go_to_url_tool(url=\\'https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine3/issues/1432\\')\",\\n  \"observation\": \"Tile: Run batch mode on linux HPC \\\\u00b7 Issue #1432 \\\\u00b7 mzmine/mzmine\\\\n            [Start of page]\\\\n\\\\nWrite better code with AI\\\\n\\\\nEnterprise-grade 24/7 support\\\\n\\\\n# Search code, repositories, users, issues, pull requests...\\\\n\\\\nWe read every piece of feedback, and take your input very seriously.\\\\n\\\\nInclude my email address so I can be contacted\\\\n\\\\n## Use saved searches to filter your results more quickly\\\\n\\\\nTo see all available qualifiers, see our documentation.\\\\n\\\\nYou signed in with another tab or window. Reload to refresh your session.\\\\n\\\\nYou signed out in another tab or window. Reload to refresh your session.\\\\n\\\\nYou switched accounts on another tab or window. Reload to refresh your session.\\\\n\\\\nYou must be signed in to change notification settings\\\\n\\\\n143\\\\n\\\\n227\\\\n\\\\n278\\\\n\\\\n35\\\\n\\\\n0\\\\n\\\\nThere was an error while loading. Please reload this page.\\\\n\\\\n# Run batch mode on linux HPC #1432\\\\n\\\\nRun batch mode on linux HPC#1432\\\\n\\\\nadd\\\\\\\\_documentationthis should be added to the documentationthis should be added to the documentation\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: @song-sbio]\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: @song-sbio]\\\\n\\\\nopened on Jul 17, 2023\\\\n\\\\nHi, I\\'m new to HPC and also MZmine 3. I would like to run batch mode to process a large number of samples for alignment and peak picking. I found command line instructions for Windows and MacOS (https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine\\\\\\\\_documentation/commandline\\\\\\\\_tool.html), but could not find similar instructions for linux. Would be grateful if similar instructions can be provided for linux system. Thank you!\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: lisakmalins]\\\\n\\\\n### lisakmalins commented on Jul 21, 2023\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: @lisakmalins]\\\\n\\\\non Jul 21, 2023\\\\n\\\\nHi @song-sbio, the process for running MZmine3 in batch mode on Linux is very similar to Windows and MacOS. E.g., if your MZmine3 executable is located at `/opt/mzmine-linux-installer/bin/MZmine` and you have a batch file named `my_batch_file.xml`, you can execute the batch file on the command line with the following command:\\\\n\\\\n/opt/mzmine-linux-installer/bin/MZmine --batch my_batch_file.xml\\\\n\\\\nYou can also view the arguments and help text with the following:\\\\n\\\\n/opt/mzmine-linux-installer/bin/MZmine --help\\\\n\\\\nThat\\'s how I\\'ve been running batch files on my Linux desktop, but your setup could be different. Do you have MZmine3 already installed, and if so did you use one of the installer versions or the portable version? Do you have a graphical user interface for your Linux HPC, or can you only access it through a command-line interface?\\\\n\\\\n\\\\ud83d\\\\udc4dReact with \\\\ud83d\\\\udc4d1SteffenHeu\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: song-sbio]\\\\n\\\\n### song-sbio commented on Aug 11, 2023\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: @song-sbio]\\\\n\\\\non Aug 11, 2023\\\\n\\\\nHi @lisakmalins Thank you so much for answering my question. So I need to convert all my mzML files into one .xml file? Would you mind sharing with me some information on how to convert multiple mzML files into one xml file? I couldn\\'t find how to do it online. Thank you very much!\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: lisakmalins]\\\\n\\\\n### lisakmalins commented on Aug 15, 2023\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: @lisakmalins]\\\\n\\\\non Aug 15, 2023\\\\n\\\\nHi @song-sbio, happy to help!\\\\n\\\\nI see the confusion -- no, the XML file (called a \\\\\"batch file\\\\\") isn\\'t a data file. It\\'s like a script or a recipe that lists all the steps that you want MZmine3 to run. In the graphical user interface of MZmine3, you can go to **Project** > **Batch mode** and then select modules to add to the batch queue. Once you have all the steps that you want to run, you can export the batch queue into an XML-format batch file to save it for later.\\\\n\\\\nThe only way to run MZmine3 through a command line interface is to create a batch file in the graphical user interface first, then call MZmine3 with the name of the batch file (using a command like in my last comment), and then MZmine3 will run through all the steps. You can also run batch files in the graphical user interface, which is useful if you want to set up an analysis that will take awhile and let it run while you\\'re away from your computer.\\\\n\\\\nYou mentioned you are new to MZmine3 -- have you seen this MZmine3 workshop on YouTube? It includes links to download the data that was used, which is small enough to process on a laptop or desktop. It doesn\\'t go into detail on command-line use, bu\",\\n  \"reward\": 1.0\\n}\\n```\\n\\n\\n================================================================================\\n\\nContent from https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine/issues/1827: \\n```json\\n{\\n  \"action\": \"go_to_url_tool(url=\\'https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine/issues/1827\\')\",\\n  \"observation\": \"Tile: Login in command line batch mode? \\\\u00b7 Issue #1827 \\\\u00b7 mzmine/mzmine\\\\n            [Start of page]\\\\n\\\\nWrite better code with AI\\\\n\\\\nEnterprise-grade 24/7 support\\\\n\\\\n# Search code, repositories, users, issues, pull requests...\\\\n\\\\nWe read every piece of feedback, and take your input very seriously.\\\\n\\\\nInclude my email address so I can be contacted\\\\n\\\\n## Use saved searches to filter your results more quickly\\\\n\\\\nTo see all available qualifiers, see our documentation.\\\\n\\\\nYou signed in with another tab or window. Reload to refresh your session.\\\\n\\\\nYou signed out in another tab or window. Reload to refresh your session.\\\\n\\\\nYou switched accounts on another tab or window. Reload to refresh your session.\\\\n\\\\nYou must be signed in to change notification settings\\\\n\\\\n143\\\\n\\\\n227\\\\n\\\\n278\\\\n\\\\n35\\\\n\\\\n0\\\\n\\\\nThere was an error while loading. Please reload this page.\\\\n\\\\n# Login in command line batch mode? #1827\\\\n\\\\nLogin in command line batch mode?#1827\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: @bsedio]\\\\n\\\\n[IMAGE: @bsedio]\\\\n\\\\nopened on May 3, 2024\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 My operating system and version: Texas Advanced Computing Center, Frontera supercomputer (Linux)\\\\n\\\\n\\\\u2022 My mzmine version: MZmine-4.0.8\\\\n\\\\nI ran MZmine-4.0.8 in batch mode on the Frontera supercomputer for the first time (using \\'slurm\\'). I\\'ve attached the batch file and slurm file as text file (since GitHub won\\'t allow me to upload .slurm or .mzba